Overall results indicate that no building was found to show high performance in all capitals except within manufactured capital. It may be because related indicators were not characterised based on proximity but on actual walking distances, residents in 25 buildings could reach every facility in five minutes and were assigned a score of 1 during normalisation. Additionally, there is an apparent distinction between private and public housing especially for indicators related to social and financial capitals. Most of the high-performance buildings in Fig. 3d and Fig. 3f belong to the private housing. All high-performance buildings located in Sha Tin centre scored high in all capitals except natural capital. Low performance buildings were found in Mei Tin, located near the Lower Shing Mun Reservoir, scoring very less in all capitals. Box plot (Fig.4
                        ) illustrates the variability in the normalised scores of each capital. Manufactured capital varies much less compared to other capitals. It may be because, all infrastructures in Hong Kong are quite close to each other due to space constraints. Outside manufactured capital, scores are more consistent in human capital at both levels, while financial capital is the most variable especially at upper levels. This might be due to the income disparity in Hong Kong economy. The indicators that lead to these variations, corresponding stakeholders and councils are listed in the priority table below (Table 2
                        ).
